04761nam a22006615i 9780691187204DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20181996nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911872047 a10.1515/97806911872042doi  a(DE-B1597)501883  a(OCoLC)1076417307  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aHIS0130002bisacsh04a338.1/09442231 aHoffman, Philip T., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGrowth in a Traditional Society :bThe French Countryside, 1450-1815 /cPhilip T. Hoffman. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4c©1996  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Princeton Economic History of the Western World ;v700tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tTables -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER One. Peasants, Historians, and Economic Growth -- tCHAPTER Two. Common Rights and the Village Community -- tCHAPTER Three. Labor Markets, Rental Markets, and Credit in the Local Economy -- tCHAPTER Four. Agricultural Productivity in France, 1450-1789 -- tCHAPTER Five. Explaining Productivity in a Traditional Economy -- tCHAPTER Six. Conclusion -- tAPPENDIX A The Methods and Sources Used with the Notre Dame Sample -- tAPPENDIX Β Measuring TFP with Other Samples of Leases -- tAPPENDIX C The Economics of Urban Fertilizer -- tAPPENDIX D Hedonic Wage Regressions -- tNotes -- tSources and Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPhilip Hoffman shatters the widespread myth that traditional agricultural societies in early modern Europe were socially and economically stagnant and ultimately dependent on wide-scale political revolution for their growth. Through a richly detailed historical investigation of the peasant agriculture of ancien-régime France, the author uncovers evidence that requires a new understanding of what constituted economic growth in such societies. His arguments rest on a measurement of long-term growth that enables him to analyze the economic, institutional, and political factors that explain its forms and rhythms. In comparing France with England and Germany, Hoffman arrives at fresh answers to some classic questions: Did French agriculture lag behind farming in other countries? If so, did the obstacles in French agriculture lurk within peasant society itself, in the peasants' culture, in their communal property rights, or in the small scale of their farms? Or did the obstacles hide elsewhere, in politics, in the tax system, or in meager opportunities for trade? The author discovers that growth cannot be explained by culture, property rights, or farm size, and argues that the real causes of growth derived from politics and gains from trade. By challenging other widely held beliefs, such as the nature of the commons and the workings of the rural economy, Hoffman offers a new analysis of peasant society and culture, one based on microeconomics and game theory and intended for a wide range of social scientists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAgricultural productivityzFrancexHistory. 0aAgriculturexEconomic aspectszFrancexHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691187204zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691187204423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691187204.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA